cmd/seekwatcher: use Axes.clear() matplot API instead of Axes.hold()

Axes.hold() disappeared in modern matplot. I'm not sure .clear()
is a direct equivalent. But it still does depder nice movices.
At least not everything is broken.

cmd/seekwatcher: avoid floating point values for rows/columns

It's a remnant of distant past when of python2 when 'int / int' gave 'int'.
In python3 it's a float nowadays:

    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "bin/seekwatcher", line 1158, in <module>
        a = subplot(*plot)
      File "matplotlib/pyplot.py", line 1268, in subplot
        key = SubplotSpec._from_subplot_args(fig, args)
      File "matplotlib/gridspec.py", line 597, in _from_subplot_args
        gs = GridSpec._check_gridspec_exists(figure, rows, cols)
      File "matplotlib/gridspec.py", line 225, in _check_gridspec_exists
        return GridSpec(nrows, ncols, figure=figure)
      File "matplotlib/gridspec.py", line 387, in __init__
        height_ratios=height_ratios)
      File "/matplotlib/gridspec.py", line 50, in __init__
        f"Number of rows must be a positive integer, not {nrows!r}")
    ValueError: Number of rows must be a positive integer, not 5.0

Let's use '//' to get integer results back.

cmd/seekwatcher: use 'is None' comparison, not '== None'

Noticed by cityvigil.

PEP-8 suggests always using `is` for singletons:
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#programming-recommendations

numpy arrays is one example where `is` is different from `==` as mentioned in:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14247373/python-none-comparison-should-i-use-is-or

Closes: https://github.com/trofi/seekwatcher/issues/3

The option is gone in:
> commit 0cfc3e7dd70ad1fc2bd241d41db548c47080645b
> Author: Chris Mason <chris.mason@oracle.com>
> Date:   Tue Sep 1 09:01:06 2009 -0400
>

So just drop all references to 'options.file'
